# Backend Protection Rule

## CRITICAL: Do NOT Modify Backend Code

**The Prelura Swift app must NEVER modify backend code, GraphQL schema, or API endpoints.**

### Why This Rule Exists
- The backend is shared by multiple apps (Flutter app, web, etc.). **Backend repo:** https://github.com/VoltisLab/prelura-app
- The Swift app talks to the API at `https://prelura.voltislabs.uk/graphql/`
- Other applications depend on the existing backend structure
- Modifying the backend would break compatibility with other clients

### What This Means
1. **DO NOT** modify GraphQL schema files
2. **DO NOT** change API endpoints or URLs
3. **DO NOT** alter backend query/mutation structures
4. **DO NOT** modify server-side code if any exists in this repository

### What You CAN Do
- ✅ Add GraphQL client code to the Swift app
- ✅ Create queries/mutations that match the existing schema
- ✅ Parse responses from the existing API
- ✅ Use the same endpoint: `https://prelura.voltislabs.uk/graphql/`
- ✅ Add Swift-specific networking/parsing code

### Integration Approach
When integrating with the backend:
- Use the existing GraphQL endpoint as-is
- Query the same schema that the Flutter app uses
- Only add client-side code (Swift networking, models, parsing)
- Treat the backend as a read-only API (from our perspective)

### Reference
- **Backend repository (server code; do not modify from this client):** https://github.com/VoltisLab/prelura-app
- **API base (this app points here):** `https://prelura.voltislabs.uk/graphql/`
- **Backend secrets:** `OPENAI_API_KEY` is set in the backend repo for LLM features; the Swift app never uses the key directly.
- **Lenny system prompt (canonical):** `docs/lenny-system-prompt.txt` in this repo — backend should use as OpenAI system message.
- Flutter app GraphQL config: `/Users/user/prelura-workspace/PreluraApp/lib/core/di.dart`

**Remember: We are adding a new client, not modifying the server.**
